This weekend marked one year since Ron’s VR, and what a rollercoaster it’s been!
From the high of great news during surgery resulting in a double vas to vas reconnection, we left on cloud 9!
But then came a series of lows. Recovering from surgery was brutal! Ron says it was 5X worse than the initial vasectomy. After 4 weeks our first analysis came back with crushing news… 0 motility. The surgery worked, but with 0 motility our chance of getting pregnant was also 0. 
I never shared this… but we debated (very briefly) putting our wedding on hold until we knew this was going to work! I wanted a child together more than anything! We were hurt, there were tears… but we relied heavily on our faith instead of letting fear destroy us. 
The next month was slightly better. Slowly improving until reaching OFF the chart numbers in July. It was no surprise when we got pregnant with Jolie Joy early August. But then the most devastating blow. Miscarriage. Heartbreaking in any situation. But after trying so hard, it was absolutely not what either of us expected. 
6 weeks weeks later, we tried again and the rest is history!
There have been highs, there have been lows… and we’d go through it all over again to get where we are RIGHT NOW! 🌈🌈
—
I’ve met a lot of people considering this journey since I started sharing about our VR. Know that I am an open book and happy to share more if you have any questions. My inbox is always open!
—
[For the sake of sharing wise information, I must note a vasectomy is meant to be permanent! Reversal is a very expensive, very painful process and in no way guarantees a baby!Please never use a vasectomy as birth control with the intent of reversing it later. Especially based on one positive outcome!!]

Because today wraps up mental health awareness month and I pride myself of being authentic, you get this:
The internet makes it SO easy to just share the good parts; the happy parts. To make it appear like you’re keeping it all together… even when you’re falling apart. But not many of us can truthfully say that’s how our lives are every day! 
I’ll never forgot Ron’s birthday trip to New York in Dec 2022. It started out on a high! We love to travel and neither of us had been to NYC in years! We’d found out just a week ago our rainbow baby was on the way… all was well in the world. Then on his birthday… something started to feel off. I didn’t want to ruin my husbands special day. But I also coudlnt handle the worry on my own and told him I felt like something was wrong. The next evening I was gushing blood, staying in time square and finding any way possible to get to the ER. I was sure we were losing our second baby in 3 months…
Anyone that’s been following knows that’s not how the evening played out (thank God 🙌🏽) cuz I’m still very pregnant (31 one weeks with a healthy active babe!) But for that night, and the 11 weeks that followed we were living in a kind of hell on earth. Every bleed felt like the worst was happening. Every doctors visit I left with the notes “threatened miscarriage” and it took such a mental toll... on both of us. We relied solely on Hope and Faith… because what else could we do?!
So I share this for a few reasons…
1. It’s really easy to share the fun stuff but remember you’re usually only getting a piece of someone’s full story. I’ve only shared the “good parts” of my rainbow pregnancy up until now! But the scary stuff, the hard parts.. make you vulnerable. And most people aren’t willing to subject themselves to the judgment that comes with vulnerability. Don’t compare your WHOLE life to just the GOOD PARTS of someone else’s!
2. To potentially give another mama HOPE! SCH pregnancy is terrifying! I’d go so far as to say crippling. Carrying this little life knowing it might not make it and all you can do is wait. Every day feels like a week. 😖 But there is hope. I cried, I begged and prayed…

I’ve got my two little girls! My rainbow baby is here and healthy and we got 11 extra days to love her on the outside. 🙏🏽😅An amazing husband. And 5 step children, each fabulous in their own special way. [I’m more than half way to the 12 kids I grew up saying I wanted.😂]

Christmas is a time of 𝙷𝙾𝙿𝙴! ✨
The Hope of a savior. The Hope of happy new year. 
And for me, Hope… in the form of my daughter!
Last Christmas I was going through the motions. 
I was hurting inside after my miscarriage earlier in the year. I’d planned to dress a bump at Christmas, take shilloutette photos in front of the tree… but instead my belly was flat.
I was keeping the secret that I was pregnant again, but had 3 appts in the December weeks leading to Christmas Day that all confirmed, we had a 50% chance of losing this baby too. 
We found out her gender early… just incase we lost her. I wanted a gender, and a name to remember…if I had to live the unthinkable twice.
But she’s here. 
Inspite of the loss before her, 
and inspite of subchorionic hemmorage. 
She was in the positive half of the 50% chance; praise God!
I share so that you too might have Hope this Christmas. 
This Holiday season might be hard, but a LOT can change in a year.
Merry Christmas my friends; never lose hope!
